## 🧩 1. Inventory Batching (Greedy + Sorting)

### 📌 Problem
Group items into batches of 3 such that:
- Each batch has exactly 3 items
- `max - min ≤ 2`

Return `true` if all items can be grouped, else `false`.

---

### 🧠 Key Idea
- Sort the array
- Check every consecutive group of 3

---

### ✅ Approach
1. Sort items  
2. If `n % 3 != 0` → return false  
3. For every group of 3:
   - check `items[i+2] - items[i] <= 2`

---

### 💻 Code

```java
import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public boolean canFormBatches(int[] items) {
        Arrays.sort(items);

        if (items.length % 3 != 0) return false;

        for (int i = 0; i < items.length; i += 3) {
            if (items[i + 2] - items[i] > 2) return false;
        }

        return true;
    }
}
❌ Mistakes Made
Used items.sort() ❌
Wrong condition: items[i] - items[i+2] ❌
🎯 Pattern

Greedy + Sorting

🧩 2. Highly Active Users (Sliding Window + HashMap)
📌 Problem

Find users who performed:

At least 3 "login" actions
Within any 60-second window

Return user IDs sorted lexicographically.

🧠 Key Idea
Group logs by user
Sort timestamps
Use sliding window of size 3
✅ Approach
Map user → login timestamps
Sort timestamps

Check window:

times[i+2] - times[i] <= 60
Add user if condition satisfied
Sort result
💻 Code
import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public List<String> highlyActiveUsers(String[] logs) {

        Map<String, List<Integer>> map = new HashMap<>();

        for (String log : logs) {
            String[] parts = log.split(" ");
            String user = parts[0];
            String action = parts[1];
            int time = Integer.parseInt(parts[2]);

            if (action.equals("login")) {
                map.putIfAbsent(user, new ArrayList<>());
                map.get(user).add(time);
            }
        }

        List<String> result = new ArrayList<>();

        for (String user : map.keySet()) {
            List<Integer> times = map.get(user);

            if (times.size() < 3) continue;

            Collections.sort(times);

            for (int i = 0; i <= times.size() - 3; i++) {
                if (times.get(i + 2) - times.get(i) <= 60) {
                    result.add(user);
                    break;
                }
            }
        }

        Collections.sort(result);
        return result;
    }
}
❌ Mistakes Made
Used == for string comparison ❌
Counted total logins instead of window ❌
Missed sorting timestamps ❌
🎯 Pattern

Sliding Window + HashMap

🧩 3. Most Frequent 3-Sequence (Hard)
📌 Problem

Find the most frequent sequence of 3 products:

Purchased by the same user
In strictly increasing timestamp order
Count each sequence once per user

If tie → return lexicographically smallest sequence.

🧠 Key Idea
Group by user
Sort by time
Generate all combinations of size 3
Count globally
✅ Approach
Map user → list of (time, product)
Sort each user’s list by time
Generate all 3-sequences
Use a set to avoid duplicates per user
Count frequency globally
Return max frequency (lex smallest if tie)
💻 Code
import java.util.*;

class Solution {

    class Pair {
        int time;
        String product;

        Pair(int time, String product) {
            this.time = time;
            this.product = product;
        }
    }

    public List<String> mostFrequentSequence(String[] logs) {

        Map<String, List<Pair>> map = new HashMap<>();

        for (String log : logs) {
            String[] parts = log.split(" ");
            String user = parts[0];
            String product = parts[1];
            int time = Integer.parseInt(parts[2]);

            map.putIfAbsent(user, new ArrayList<>());
            map.get(user).add(new Pair(time, product));
        }

        Map<String, Integer> countMap = new HashMap<>();

        for (String user : map.keySet()) {

            List<Pair> list = map.get(user);
            if (list.size() < 3) continue;

            Collections.sort(list, (a, b) -> a.time - b.time);

            List<String> products = new ArrayList<>();
            for (Pair p : list) {
                products.add(p.product);
            }

            Set<String> seen = new HashSet<>();

            int n = products.size();

            for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
                for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
                    for (int k = j + 1; k < n; k++) {

                        String seq = products.get(i) + "," +
                                     products.get(j) + "," +
                                     products.get(k);

                        if (seen.add(seq)) {
                            countMap.put(seq, countMap.getOrDefault(seq, 0) + 1);
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        String best = "";
        int max = 0;

        for (String seq : countMap.keySet()) {
            int freq = countMap.get(seq);

            if (freq > max || (freq == max && seq.compareTo(best) < 0)) {
                best = seq;
                max = freq;
            }
        }

        return Arrays.asList(best.split(","));
    }
}
❌ Mistakes Made
Wrong data structure ❌
Lost timestamp ordering ❌
Missed uniqueness per user ❌
Syntax issues ❌
🎯 Pattern

HashMap + Sorting + Combination
